        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m post-acquisition owner-CEO with 14 months operating history. Can I qualify yet?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Borderline. Most B3-3.4-02 S-corp / partnership qualifying requires 2-year (24-month) entity history at the acquired company. We can sometimes qualify at 12-24 months with strong Q of E documentation supporting the acquired company financial profile, but full 24-month history typically produces strongest outcome. Alternative: Bank Statement Non-QM on 12-24 months of operating company business bank statements.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Does the SBA 7(a) personal guarantee affect my DTI?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, the SBA 7(a) personal guarantee creates contingent liability that factors into mortgage underwriting DTI calculation. The SBA 7(a) debt service itself flows through the operating company P&amp;L (not personal payment obligation) but the guarantee remains personal. We document the structure carefully and coordinate the residential mortgage close timing relative to SBA 7(a) close.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need for a business acquirer mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Depends on stage. Pre-search corporate: two W-2s, current pay stubs, HR letter. Search Fund / ETA: Search Fund LLC W-2, investor capital documentation, search fund agreement, carry vesting schedule. Self-Funded Searcher: brokerage statements showing liquid reserves, prior W-2 / Schedule C history, SBA 7(a) pre-approval if at acquisition stage. Independent Sponsor: 1099-NECs from each portfolio company, Schedule C / S-corp 1120-S, partnership documents, carry recognition history. Post-acquisition: acquired company tax returns (Form 1120-S or 1065) with K-1s, partnership/S-corp agreement, SBA 7(a) loan documentation, Q of E report.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My acquisition includes goodwill amortization. How is that treated post-close?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Acquisition-related goodwill amortization at the acquired company entity level is non-cash deduction. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a>, Form 1084 cash-flow addbacks systematically recover goodwill amortization at the S-corp / partnership level. For acquisitions producing substantial goodwill (common at premium-multiple acquisitions), the addback recovery can be substantial. We document the acquisition purchase price allocation supporting the goodwill amortization schedule.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My SBA 7(a) acquisition has DSCR requirement. How does that interact with mortgage qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">SBA 7(a) DSCR (Debt Service Coverage Ratio) requirements typically 1.15x minimum at the operating company level. The DSCR documentation supports operating company income narrative and indirectly supports owner-CEO post-acquisition K-1 qualifying. We coordinate with the SBA lender for DSCR documentation continuity and consistent narrative across SBA 7(a) and residential mortgage underwriting.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for business acquirers?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No &mdash; mortgage rates for business acquirers are the same as for any other borrower at the same credit profile, loan amount, and program selection. Conventional Conforming and Jumbo achieve standard pricing. Non-QM products (Asset-Depletion, Bank Statement) carry rate premium reflecting specialty underwriting framework but aren&rsquo;t acquirer-specific.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m planning to launch a Search Fund in 6 months. Should I buy now or wait?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Strongly recommend closing residential BEFORE Search Fund launch. Pre-launch you have established corporate / MBA W-2 history supporting strong Conventional qualifying. Post-launch your income transitions to lower search-phase Search Fund LLC W-2 ($80K-$120K vs prior corporate $250K-$400K) which substantially reduces qualifying capacity. The pre-launch window is the optimal residential close timing for almost every Search Fund / ETA path.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse has stable W-2 income. Does that help during my search phase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Substantially yes &mdash; spouse W-2 stability provides strong qualifying anchor during searcher search phase when searcher income may be lower or variable. Combined household income from spouse W-2 + searcher W-2 / Schedule C / Asset-Depletion typically produces robust qualifying capacity. Both files combine as co-borrowers with channel-appropriate analysis.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What is Quality of Earnings (Q of E) and how does it affect my mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Quality of Earnings (Q of E) reports commissioned during acquisition diligence by Big 4 firms or specialty Q of E firms validate target company EBITDA for SBA / seller / equity financing. Q of E supports multi-source verification of acquired company financial profile. For post-acquisition mortgage qualifying, Q of E documentation supports the acquired company narrative under B3-3.4-02 K-1 analysis. We coordinate with the Q of E firm where relevant.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders sometimes refuse business acquirer files?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Six reasons: (1) Search Fund LLC W-2 misread as "speculative startup" without recognizing institutional asset class structure; (2) Self-Funded Searcher Asset-Depletion path not recognized; (3) Independent Sponsor lumpy carry recognition treated as instability without 24-month averaging; (4) post-acquisition goodwill amortization treated as profitability concern without Form 1084 cash-flow addback; (5) SBA 7(a) debt service incorrectly placed in personal DTI instead of operating company P&amp;L; (6) acquisition-close timing window mishandled producing failed underwriting. The income and asset capacity is documentable.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My acquisition includes seller note. How does that affect things?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Seller notes (typically 10-25% of purchase price) provide additional acquisition financing beyond SBA 7(a) senior debt + personal down payment. Seller note debt service flows through the operating company P&amp;L similar to SBA 7(a) debt. Seller note may have subordination terms, deferred payment structure, or earnout conversion features. We document the seller note terms for full operating company P&amp;L narrative.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My Search Fund agreement has step-up acquisition mechanics. How is that documented?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Search Fund step-up acquisition mechanics (where searcher equity stake increases at acquisition close based on transaction structure) document potential post-acquisition ownership stake. The step-up structure is documented through the Search Fund agreement and acquisition equity arrangement. Post-acquisition K-1 documentation reflects the actual ownership percentage achieved through the step-up mechanic.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m at an Independent Sponsor with multiple in-flight deals. How do you document the portfolio?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Independent Sponsor portfolio documentation covers each in-flight portfolio company: management fee structure for each deal, equity raised from LP base, carry terms (15-20% above 8% preferred hurdle typical), and current operating status. We document the active portfolio through partnership documents, 1099-NECs from each portfolio company, and Schedule C / S-corp returns reflecting the multi-deal income aggregation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I use bank statements alone instead of tax returns?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes through Bank Statement Program Non-QM for high-deduction Independent Sponsors or owner-CEOs. 12 or 24 months of business bank statements qualify under the Bank Statement framework. Useful when entity-level deductions are substantial enough that Form 1084 addbacks alone don&rsquo;t produce desired qualifying income. Pricing carries 0.75-1.5% rate premium vs Conventional.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My acquisition included earnout to seller. How does that affect post-acquisition qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Earnout to seller (typically 1-3 years post-close tied to EBITDA milestones) creates additional acquisition financing obligation at the operating company level. Earnout payments flow through the operating company P&amp;L as additional debt service. We document the earnout structure for full operating company P&amp;L narrative and ensure correct treatment in B3-3.4-02 entity analysis.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m operating multiple acquired companies under a HoldCo. How does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">HoldCo / Permanent Capital model with multiple portfolio companies under common ownership requires consolidated entity analysis. Each operating company entity Form 1120-S or 1065 with K-1s plus the HoldCo entity returns. We document the consolidated structure for full owner-CEO income narrative across the multiple portfolio companies under B3-3.4-02 aggregation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My target acquisition is in regulated industry. Does that affect anything?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Regulated industry acquisitions (healthcare, financial services, transportation, FDA-regulated, etc.) commonly require longer diligence timelines and additional regulatory approval before close. Acquisition close timing complexity increases. We coordinate residential mortgage timing accounting for the regulatory approval timeline. Post-acquisition operating in regulated industry doesn&rsquo;t affect mortgage qualifying mechanics &mdash; same B3-3.4-02 K-1 analysis applies.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I make S-corp election post-acquisition?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For acquired companies with $300K+ EBITDA, S-corp election under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/1361" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 1361</a> commonly optimal for self-employment tax savings. Typical structure: W-2 reasonable comp $120K-$200K depending on operating role + K-1 distributions representing remaining net business income. Coordinate with your CPA. S-corp election affects B3-3.4-02 entity analysis with combined W-2 + K-1 documentation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a corporate executive considering Search Fund formation in 12 months. What should I do now?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Close residential mortgage NOW using established corporate W-2 history. Pre-Search Fund formation is the optimal residential close timing using your strongest qualifying capacity (corporate $250K-$400K W-2). Post-formation your income transitions to lower Search Fund LLC W-2 ($80K-$120K) substantially reducing qualifying capacity. Strategic pre-search close locks in capacity.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 120-150 days before you intend to make an offer. Business acquirer files benefit from substantial runway because of channel-specific qualifying (Search Fund LLC W-2 vs Self-Funded Asset-Depletion vs Independent Sponsor Schedule C vs post-acquisition K-1), multi-year entity returns documentation, Form 1084 cash-flow addback analysis, possible Q of E coordination, SBA 7(a) personal guarantee DTI sequencing, and any acquisition close timing coordination.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation should I request from my Search Fund / acquisition / SBA lender?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For Search Fund / ETA: Search Fund LLC formation documents, investor capital commitment letters, search fund agreement with carry vesting terms. For acquisition: purchase price allocation, Q of E report, target company tax returns and financial statements, SBA 7(a) loan documentation, seller note terms. For post-acquisition: 12-24 months of operating company tax returns (Form 1120-S or 1065) with K-1s, partnership/S-corp agreement, operating company bank statements, current DSCR documentation, SBA 7(a) servicing status.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

